"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:6;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:17:"content marketing";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:7;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"stats";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"http://theseedstudio.com/?p=318";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:348:"You may have heard that when it comes to online marketing, content is king. 87% of all businesses are engaged in some form of <strong>content marketing&#8230; <a\nhref="http://theseednetwork.com/blog/2011/06/17/content-marketing/" class="read_more">Read the rest</a></strong>. There are 3 good reasons for this.First, people trust blog posts, videos";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Dan Logtenberg";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4467:"<p>You may have heard that when it comes to online marketing, content is king. <a\ntitle="Content Marketing Report" href="http://www.contentmarketinginstitute.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/B2B-Content-Marketing-2010-Small-Organization-Report.pdf" target="_blank">87% of all businesses</a> are engaged in some form of <strong>content marketing</strong>. There are 3 good reasons for this.</p><p><a\nhref="http://theseednetwork.com/blog/2011/06/17/content-marketing/content/" rel="attachment wp-att-320"><img\nclass="alignleft size-full wp-image-320" title="content" src="http://theseednetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/content.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="300" /></a></p><p>First, people trust blog posts, videos and reviews more than they trust advertising. 60-70% of users are more likely to buy something after reading a post or watching a video about it than after seeing an ad.</p><p>Second, content marketing is essential to improving search engine ranking. Every post you create gets indexed by Google, Bing and others, increasing your exposure for that topic and improving your website&#8217;s overall search ranking. Ads, on the other hand are essentially invisible to search engines and have no long term impact on search ranking at all.</p><p>And third, in most cases, content marketing is also less expensive than advertising.</p><h2>First, the Hard Part.</h2><p>So, if content marketing has more impact AND is cheaper, why isn&#8217;t everyone doing it?</p><p>For most people, content is a lot harder to create than an ad. You might be great at running your business and passionate about what you do, but if you&#8217;re like a lot of entrepreneurs, you clam up when you try to write it down. Creating interesting and original content takes time, and most entrepreneurs aren&#8217;t natural writers.</p><h2>The W5 Content Solution</h2><p>The easiest and arguably best way to create content is simply to answer one or more of these  questions: <strong>&#8220;Who?&#8221;</strong>, <strong>&#8220;What?&#8221;</strong>,<strong>&#8220;When?&#8221;</strong>, <strong>&#8220;Where?&#8221;</strong>, <strong>&#8220;Why?&#8221;</strong> or <strong>&#8220;How?&#8221;</strong></p><p>There are probably thousands of W questions related to your business that you can answer right now. If you&#8217;re still stuck, think about the questions your customers ask every day about your products or services.</p><h3>The Forumla:</h3><p>Here&#8217;s a formula for creating content that works for me:</p><ol><li>Every time someone asks me a question about our services, company or  industry, I write it down. I also pay attention to the answer I give and any follow-up questions and I write them down too.</li><li>I make a bulleted list of my answer, trying to make it as simple and clear as possible.</li><li>I write down where the question comes from. I might explain the story of the customer  or I might give some broader context. For example, do a lot of other people have the same question? If so, why? What does this say about my industry or service that so many people are puzzled by the same thing?</li><li>When it comes time to post to your blog, all you need to do is rewrite your notes as simply and as clearly as possible.</li><li>You may want to start with an anecdote or fact to better explain why the question matters and examples of how the answer can be used.</li><li>Format you post: reference your statements and list your sources where possible, date your work and use sub-titles. Your readers and Google will love you for it!</li></ol><p>Again, keep it simple but also keep it personal. Your readers are more likely to trust you if you sound genuine.</p><p>Have you tried content marketing? What worked for you?</p><ul><li>Here are more <a\nhref="http://www.bazaarvoice.com/resources/stats" target="_blank">stats on content and social media marketing</a>.</li><li><a\ntitle="Copy Blogger" href="http://copyblogger.com/" target="_blank">Copyblogger</a> has some great tips on <a\ntitle="Content Marketing and Copywriting" href="http://www.copyblogger.com/content-marketing-copywriting/">content marketing</a>.</li><li>Remember, everything starts with a good <a\ntitle="Online Marketing Strategy" href="http://theseedstudio.com/services/strategy-planning/">marketing strategy</a></li><li>Talk to us about our <a\ntitle="Internet Marketing Services" href="http://theseedstudio.com/services/internet-marketing/">Internet marketing services</a></li></ul> ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss"